\description{
Applies a documented, reproducible correction to one or more landmark
coordinates for a single specimen, after visual quality-control (e.g.
with \code{\link[=plot_fishmorph_points]{plot_fishmorph_points()}}) has identified a misplaced point --
rather than editing digitized coordinates by hand outside the package,
leaving no record of what changed or why. Currently implements one rule,
\code{"align"}: some landmark groups are expected, by the digitization
protocol, to share the same X or Y coordinate (e.g. points 9, 8, 11, 4,
the ventral reference line drawn by \code{\link[=plot_fishmorph_points]{plot_fishmorph_points()}}'s
\code{outline}); when one of them is visibly off, \code{correct_landmarks()} snaps
\emph{only} the specified point(s) to the median position of the other,
trusted points in the group -- it never silently decides on its own
which point is wrong.
}
\details{
\code{rule = "align"} computes the reference value as the \emph{median} (not
mean) of \code{setdiff(points, correct)}'s \code{axis} coordinate, for robustness
if one of the trusted reference points also happens to be slightly off;
with very few reference points (e.g. two), this offers little
protection and the correction should be visually re-checked afterwards.
Only \code{specimen} is modified; every other specimen's landmarks are left
untouched. As with \code{\link[=impute_landmarks]{impute_landmarks()}}, this is not a substitute for
re-digitizing from the original photograph when that is possible.

\code{rule = "check_geometry"} runs a fixed set of seven checks, of two
different kinds:

Five checks ask whether a landmark group shares the raw coordinate the
FISHMORPH protocol expects of it (\code{unit = "rel_bl"}, gated by
\code{tolerance_coord}; identical to the criterion \code{\link[=correct_geometry]{correct_geometry()}} uses
to decide what to correct): (1)-(3) each of the segments (1, 9), (3, 4),
(10, 11) should share a common X (i.e. be vertical, perpendicular to
the main body axis) -- reported as \code{perpendicular_seg_1_9_vs_axis},
\code{perpendicular_seg_3_4_vs_axis}, \code{perpendicular_seg_10_11_vs_axis}; (4)
the eye-socket line (5, 13, 7, 14, 6, 8) should likewise share a common
X, reported as \code{perpendicular_eye_vertical_vs_axis}; (5) the ventral
line (9, 8, 11, 4) should share a common Y (i.e. be horizontal,
parallel to the main axis), reported as \code{axis_horizontal_parallel}. For
each, the deviation is the absolute difference between the most
deviant point's coordinate and the shared reference value the other
point(s) agree on (median, for the two multi-point groups; a fixed
anatomical anchor, for the three two-point segments -- see
\code{\link[=correct_geometry]{correct_geometry()}}'s Details for why), expressed as a proportion of
body length (Bl, the distance between landmarks 1 and 2) so the same
default tolerance is meaningful across specimens/data sets digitized at
different scales.

Two further checks remain angular (\code{unit = "deg"}, gated by
\code{tolerance}), because they compare the \emph{orientation} of two lines
rather than asking whether a single group of points shares a
coordinate, and are deliberately sensitive to how the photograph itself
was oriented: (6) \code{eye_axis_vertical_alignment}, whether the eye-socket
line's own best-fit orientation is close to vertical \emph{in the image's
own frame} (i.e. the photograph itself looks reasonably level -- this
can, and should, fail for a validly measured but visibly rotated
photograph, which is why it is excluded from
\code{\link[=fishmorph_segments]{fishmorph_segments()}}'s \code{geometry_check} trait-NA-ing); and (7)
\code{parallel_vertical_segments}, whether segments (1,9), (3,4), (10,11),
and the eye-socket line are mutually parallel to each other (reported
as the single largest pairwise deviation among them). A line's
orientation, for these two checks, is estimated by its first principal
axis (via \code{\link[stats:prcomp]{stats::prcomp()}}), which reduces to the exact two-point
direction for two-landmark segments and is a robust fit for the
longer, multi-landmark lines.

Specimens missing a landmark needed by a given check yield \code{NA} for
that check rather than an error (mirroring the rest of the package's
tolerance of missing landmarks, e.g. \code{outline} in
\code{\link[=plot_fishmorph_points]{plot_fishmorph_points()}}); the five coordinate checks additionally
yield \code{NA} if landmark 1 or 2 (needed to compute Bl) is missing.
}
